# {{PROJECT_NAME}} — Agent Workflow

This document governs which agent identity authors, implements, and audits work in this repository.

## Principle

Role is not identity.

- Author, implementer, and auditor are roles.
- Claude, Codex, Gemini, or any other runtime are identities.
- The identity that authored a unit of work does not act as the primary auditor for that same unit.

A unit of work can be:
- a work-order plan
- an implementation
- a canon revision
- a phase-close package

## Default Assignment Matrix

Adapt this matrix to the project, but keep the role-separation rule intact.

| Work shape | Default author / implementer | Default primary auditor |
|---|---|---|
| governance docs, harness wiring, UX copy, broad greenfield scaffolding | Claude | Codex |
| dense single-file refactors, algorithmic logic, measurement-heavy migrations | Codex | Claude audit agents |
| security-sensitive or compliance-heavy work | whichever identity is authoring | companion identity required |
| prompt or agent-instruction changes | authoring identity | companion identity plus product-drift review |

## Flip Triggers

Explicitly consider flipping the default assignment when any of these apply:

1. Three failed audit rounds on the same unit
2. Author-fatigue signals: stale counts, naming drift, repeated misses
3. Substrate-fit mismatch: another identity clearly fits the work better

Flips should be explicit. Do not silently change author/auditor roles midstream.

## Handoff Protocol

When work changes hands, the sending agent must provide:

1. Prior audit history
2. Concrete anchor artifacts
3. Exact scope and non-goals
4. Deliverable shape

Anchor artifacts include the things the receiver should trust:
- baseline files
- counts
- commit hashes
- failing test output
- file lists

The receiving agent's output is reviewed through a fresh audit round, not silently edited into a different result.

## Degraded Mode

If the companion identity is unavailable:

1. State that review is running in degraded mode
2. Use the available internal auditors as supplemental review
3. Do not claim full closure on high-risk work until cross-identity audit happens

## Required Metadata

Every WO should record:
- author identity
- intended auditor identity
- work tier
- whether degraded mode was used

## Anti-Patterns

- The same identity authors and audits the same unit
- A subagent from the same identity is treated as cross-identity review
- A handoff result is silently edited instead of re-audited
- The team keeps retrying the same failing author/auditor pairing without flipping roles
- Degraded mode is used but not disclosed

## Relationship To Audit Protocol

`docs/planning/AUDIT-PROTOCOL.md` defines when audits run.
This document defines who should perform them.
